            <p>
               <supplied reason="undefined">Διοκλητιανὸς</supplied>
               <lb/>καὶ Μαξιμιαν<supplied reason="undefined">ὸς</supplied>
               <lb/>
               <expan><abbr>σεβ</abbr><ex>αστοὶ</ex></expan> καὶ<lb/>Κωστάντιο<supplied reason="undefined">ς</supplied>
               <lb/>Επιφανέστατοι<lb/>καίσαρες <space/>
               <lb/>λίθον <supplied reason="undefined">δ</supplied>ιορί<lb/>
               <supplied reason="undefined">ζον</supplied>
               <unclear>τα ἀγρο</unclear>
               <supplied reason="undefined">ὺς or ὅρους</supplied>
               <lb/>
               <gap reason="illegible"/>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b2"
              xml:id="kafr0010.translation"
              corresp="#kafr0010.transcription">
            <p>[Diocletian] and Maximian, Augusti, and Constantius...illustrious Caesars (have erected this) stone demarking (the) fields [or boundaries] (of)...
				</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Inscription of this boundary stone originally published in 1978 without translation by S. Applebaum, B. Isaac and Y. Landau. No measurements are given. One name in the inscription is missing. If the omitted name is that Galerius, the Diocletianic marker can be dated to 293-305 CE. In the transcriptin the abbreviation for οεββ is retained, but it is completed in the translation.</p>
         </div>
